title: Add Trilu custom op
body:
Add Trilu custom op that combines Tril and Triu operators.
Triu returns the upper triangular part of a matrix and Tril returns the lower part of a matrix, the other elements of a result matrix are set to 0.
Trilu op is required for export of some transformers pytorch models.

PyTorch reference:
torch.tril: https://pytorch.org/docs/master/generated/torch.tril.html
torch.triu: https://pytorch.org/docs/master/generated/torch.triu.html

title: Revise Send and Recv
body:
**Description**: Describe your changes.
Retrieve static shapes computed from memory planning step and use it in Send and Recv. If all Recv's output shapes are inferred, the associated Send-Recv pair may skip the communication for shape information.

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
It saves 3 MPI calls in Send and Recv. Send and Recv are also revised so that refactorizing them with NCCL will be easier.

**Test**
- Running on the following command, you will see the same loss before and after this PR.

/bert_ort/openmpi/bin/mpirun -n 3 --tag-output ./onnxruntime_training_bert --model_name /bert_ort/bert_models/nv/bert-tiny/bert-tiny-uncased_L_3_H_128_A_2_V_30528_S_512_Dp_0.1_optimized_layer_norm_opset12 --train_data_dir /bert_data/512/books_wiki_en_corpus/train --test_data_dir /bert_data/512/books_wiki_en_corpus/test --train_batch_size 12 --mode train --display_loss_steps 1 --optimizer lamb --learning_rate 0.006 --gradient_accumulation_steps 16 --num_train_steps 16 --warmup_ratio 0 --warmup_mode Linear --use_nccl --pipeline_parallel_size 3  --cut_group_info 186:71-273,308:71-395 --seed 5

title: Avoid duplicated calls of postprocess in training frontend
body: It is possible that postprocesses are called multiple times where the provided model is not onnx model, while `load_state_dict` is called from user. (The code will first create an onnx model, and apply postprocesses. It will then initialize the session and apply postprocesses again). The update moves the call to postprocesses such that they are only called when `onnx_model_` is created. To ensure that for any given onnx model the postprocesses are only called once.

title: Shape independent gradient builder for ops requiring broadcast
body:
This PR adds support for gradient building when shape inference fails, for the following ops: 

MatMul
Gemm
AddSub
Mul
BiasGelu
Div
Expand
Transpose

Current behavior relies on shape inference to calculate the axes to be reduced when there was a broadcast in the forward pass of the op. This change uses the BroadcastGradientArgs op to dynamically calculate the reduction axes, and the ReduceSumTraining op that accepts this as an input instead of an attribute.

Collaboration with @ytaous

title: Disable GPU Timeouts for DirectX/DML sessions in WinML
body:
Disable GPU Timeouts for DirectX/DML sessions in WinML

Issue: Long running ML tasks in WinML timeout after 2 seconds. Note, if they are preempted by the gpu, the 2 second time resets, and can afford the ML task more time. This can lead to transient behavior, where ML tasks sometimes complete succesfully, and other times TDR.

Fix: Disable 2 second timeout with queueDesc.Flags = D3D12_COMMAND_QUEUE_FLAG_DISABLE_GPU_TIMEOUT; when creating the CommandQueue.

title: Update ModelDescription and minor fix on ORTTrainer ctor
body:
This PR keeps the public API intact, but changes how model description is stored on the backend

Currently, users creates a dict with two lists of tuples. One list called 'inputs' and each tuple has the following format tuple(name, shape). The second list is called 'outputs' and each tuple can be either tuple(name, shape) or tuple(name, shape, is_loss).

With this PR, when this dict is passed in to ORTTrainer, it is fully validated as usual. However, tuples are internally replaced by namedtuples and all output tuples will have tuple(name, shape, is_loss) format instead of is_loss being optionally present.

Additionally to that normalization in the internal representation (which eases coding), two internal methods were created to replace a namedtuple(name, shape) to namedtuple(name, shape, dtype) or namedtuple(name, shape, is_loss, dtype) dependeing whether the tuple is an input or output.

This is necessary as ORTTRainer finds out data types of each input/output during model export to onnx.

Finally, a minor fix was done on ORTTrainer. It could initialize ORTTrainerOptions incorrectly when options=None

title: [Proposal] constexpr OpSchema
body:
This PR is more aimed at discussing possibilities for constexpr construction of OpSchemas than the code itself. The code change is a prototype on how it could be implemented.

Code for registration makes up for a decent amount of code and SymbolSort shows registration functions as the largest ones in the binary. Currently, we build the OpSchema object dynamically using the API exposed by the onnx submodule. Constructing it field by field with individual calls isn't the best for binary size or runtime; furthermore, onnx makes a bunch of copies (they use e.g. strings for storage of text, which while convenient,  will make a copy of the string literals we pass in; it could simply a reference/pointer/view to it instead when we're passing constant, static values).

The proposal is to rewrite OpSchema (and all the objects it contains/receives) to have constexpr variants, and support construction with no copies. Ideally this would be in onnx . In this prototype I made a separate CxOpSchema class instead of editing onnx. CxOpSchema has an API similar to OpSchema, but constexpr. I make an array of constexpr CxOpSchema during compile time, and during runtime I create OpSchemas out of them for registration.

Doing these changes to contrib ops only, I got 48640 bytes saved. More could be saved applying this to all operators, and the conversion from CxOpSchema to OpSchema can be removed if onnx supports this natively.

Ideally, onnx should also have a way to hold a string_view or a const char * to avoid copying of all strings, and spans instead of copying vectors and such. This would make registration cheaper and reduce overall memory usage. I don't know how much of a hassle it is to do these changes to onnx instead of onnxruntime; I'll leave it up to you ORT people to decide :)

The PR is huge since all operators were touched, but the relevant parts are the constexpr classes in the beginning and the conversion from CxOpSchema to OpSchema.

title: WinML should dynamically link against onnxruntime.dll and only system32 for inbox builds
body:
Issue: WinML is layered on top of onnxruntime.dll. On Inbox builds, onnxruntime.dll ships in system32. If the WinML redist is used, a version of onnxruntime (from the redist) is binplaced next to the calling application. This overrides loadlibrary search order, and calls into the Inbox Windows::AI::MachineLearning namespace are redirected to the redist onnxruntime.dll. 

Fix: Onnxruntime calls in inbox builds should always ONLY reference the system32 version of onnxruntimel.dll. To do this, the onnxruntime.dll is dynamically loaded from system32 directly on inbox builds, and using normal loadlibrary search order for redist calls.

title: Support asymmetric paddings in CUDA Conv kernel
body:
Support asymmetric padding in CUDA Conv kernel.

Problem: 
1) If pads are known at model load time (through `pad` attribute) and if they turn out to be asymmetric, we fallback to CPU EP (as CuDNN does not natively support asymmetric padding). This leads to poor performance for models containing such nodes. 
(https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/1961 https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/2313 https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/3221)

2) If pads have to be computed dynamically at Run() time (through `auto_pad` attribute) and if they turn out to be asymmetric, we make the pad symmetric and introduce noise which leads to output data not aligning with expected output values (https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/4488)

Solution:
Implement @joba01's idea (https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/3414#issuecomment-622040645) into the CUDA Conv kernel

Motivation:
Fixes https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/4488 https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/3221 https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/2313 and partially mitigates https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/1961 (the perf of YoloV3 improved by ~ 20%)

title: support data parallel + pipeline parallel
body:
**Description**: Describe your changes.
This change adds support to run pipeline parallel together with data parallel. Tested with Bert-L and the corresponding unit tests are added. 

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
Previously pipeline parallel and data parallel are incompatible. Ort can only run one or the other. Now with a node of m x n GPUs, it can run m data parallel and n pipeline parallel. 

The command to run Bert-Large is as below:

/bert_ort/openmpi/bin/mpirun --report-pid - -n 4 ./onnxruntime_training_bert --model_name /bert_ort/bert_models/nv/bert-large/bert-large-uncased_L_24_H_1024_A_16_V_30528_S_512_Dp_0.1_optimized_layer_norm_opset12 --train_data_dir /bert_data/512/books_wiki_en_corpus/train --test_data_dir /bert_data/512/books_wiki_en_corpus/test --train_batch_size 1 --mode train --display_loss_steps 1 --optimizer lamb --learning_rate 0.006 --gradient_accumulation_steps 5 --num_train_steps 10 --warmup_ratio 0 --warmup_mode Linear --use_nccl --pipeline_parallel_size 2 --cut_group_info 1881:407-1951/2073/2195/2317/2439/2561/2683/2805/2927/3049/3171/3293 --data_parallel_size 2

- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?

Now it need nearly 2 hours.


- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.

title: Enable MatMul + Scale fusion
body:
**Description**
Update TransposeMatMul to support scaling of the matrix product by a constant scalar value (analogous to the GEMM alpha parameter). Rename TransposeMatMul to TransposeScaleMatMul.
Fuse MatMul with surrounding Mul/Div with constant scalar into TransposeScaleMatMul.

**Motivation and Context**
Performance optimization. From profiling ORT BERT large training, it was observed that elementwise divisions around MatMul's took a significant amount of time.

**Performance measurements**
baseline (d8f3e46d458397b3fb335477d3efc91e22e160d8), updated (aac2e160275269792a6330b1afd5805ec9a55fa2)

Command:
```
# phase 1
seq_len=128
batch_size=64
max_predictions_per_seq=20

# phase 2
#seq_len=512
#batch_size=10
#max_predictions_per_seq=80

./onnxruntime_training_bert \
  --model_name /bert_ort/bert_models/nv/bert-large/bert-large-uncased_L_24_H_1024_A_16_V_30528_S_512_Dp_0.1_optimized_layer_norm_opset12 \
  --train_data_dir /bert_data/${seq_len}/books_wiki_en_corpus/train --test_data_dir /bert_data/${seq_len}/books_wiki_en_corpus/test \
  --train_batch_size ${batch_size} --mode train --num_train_steps 400 --display_loss_steps 1 \
  --warmup_ratio=0.2843 --warmup_mode=Poly \
  --optimizer lamb \
  --gradient_accumulation_steps 1 \
  --max_predictions_per_seq=${max_predictions_per_seq} \
  --use_nccl \
  --use_mixed_precision --allreduce_in_fp16
```
